<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-361-314  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 361 314.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  June 15 1989 n1168 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hotline calls reveal huge hacking losses.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nicolle, Lindsay.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British victims of computer intrusion are reporting losses of upto 100,000 pounds sterling on a confidential telephone hotline setup by the Touche Ross management consulting firm.andP;  Fifty victims,mostly from the financial sector, have noted losses of between50,000 and 100,000 pounds sterling.andP;  Most victims have notreported the losses to the police because they fear adversepublicity and do not believe law enforcement is capable of dealingwith computer crime.andP;  Some victims were able to minimizedisruption with data recovery systems, but others have sufferedbadly due to lack of preparation.andP;  Touche is using the hotline togather evidence in support of a Parliamentary bill calling fortougher computer-crime laws in the UK.andP;  The consultants say thatmost of the cases involve inside hackers or employees whoaccidentally corrupt data.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Touche, Ross and Co. (surveys).andO;Topic:     Computer HackersData SecurityComputer CrimesAuditing of Computer SystemsSystem IntegrityData Integrity.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>